[h1]The z-index Property [/h1]

When elements are positioned outside the normal flow, they can overlap other elements.
The [b]z-index[/b] property specifies the stack order of an element (which element should be placed in front of, or behind, the others).

[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="577"].blue { 
   background-color: #8EC4D0;
   margin-bottom: 15px;
   width: 120px;
   height: 120px;
   color: #FFF;
}
.red {
   background-color: #FF4D4D;
   position: relative;
   width: 120px;
   height: 120px;
   color: #FFF;
   margin-top: -50px;
   margin-left: 50px;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2662" width="100%"]
[note]The red box overlaps the blue box, because it was placed [b]later [/b]in the HTML markup. 
The [b]z-index[/b] property can change this order.[/note]

[h1]Assigning the z-index Property [/h1]

Assigning a higher z-index value to the blue div and a lower z-index value to the red div will result in the following:

[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="578"].blue {
[b]   z-index: 3; [/b]
   position: relative;
}
.red {
  [b] z-index: 2;[/b]
   position: relative;
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2663" width="100%"]
[note]The z-index works [b]only [/b]on positioned elements (position:absolute, position:relative, or position:fixed).[/note]
